#compdef git-subtrac
# =============================================================================
# git-subtrac — Avery Pennarun's "all your git submodules
#          in one place" — a Go-implemented git extension
#          that solves the long-standing pain of `git
#          submodule` (which fetches submodule contents
#          from EXTERNAL repos that can move/rebase/
#          disappear) by COLLECTING the entire history
#          of every submodule recursively into a SEPARATE
#          tracking branch (named `<branch>.trac`) inside
#          the parent repository.  The parent repo's
#          `.gitmodules` then uses `url = .` (single dot)
#          to fetch submodule contents from itself,
#          eliminating the dependency on external
#          submodule URLs while preserving the standard
#          `git submodule` user experience.
#          Distinguishing from `git submodule` (default
#          git submodule mechanism; fragile because
#          submodule URLs can break), `git subtree`
#          (rewrites parent history to inline submodule
#          contents; destructive + non-reversible), `git
#          subrepo` (Ingy döt Net's git-subrepo
#          extension — similar to subtree but with
#          easier merging), and Google's `repo` tool
#          (Android's multi-repo tool — heavy ceremony,
#          not git-native) by:
#            - NON-DESTRUCTIVE — does NOT rewrite the
#              parent's history; the parent's commits
#              remain unchanged.  All collected
#              submodule content lives in SEPARATE
#              `.trac` branches; users can delete those
#              branches without affecting the parent
#            - SELF-CONTAINED REPO — after running `git
#              subtrac update` + pushing the `.trac`
#              branches + editing `.gitmodules` to
#              `url = .`, the parent repo contains
#              every blob/tree/commit needed for any
#              past or current submodule version.  Can
#              be cloned to a USB stick + restored
#              offline; no external git server required
#            - END-USER TRANSPARENCY — users cloning the
#              repo DON'T need git-subtrac installed.
#              All the standard `git submodule init/
#              update/sync/foreach` commands continue
#              to work exactly as before.  git-subtrac
#              is only needed when MAKING NEW changes
#              to submodule references
#            - GO-GIT FOUNDATION — uses go-git/go-git
#              v5 (this is the headline CLI library
#              that CONTINUES Axis 43 on the Go side;
#              see taxonomy notes below) for ALL git
#              object-graph traversal + branch-ref
#              manipulation + tree-iteration.  Pure-Go,
#              zero CGo, zero libgit2 .so dependency;
#              compiles cleanly to any GOOS/GOARCH Go
#              supports.  Uses apenwarr's own fork of
#              go-git via a `replace` directive in
#              go.mod for specific fixes
#            - RECURSIVE SUBMODULE COLLECTION — walks
#              submodules-of-submodules to arbitrary
#              depth; the entire transitive submodule
#              graph from any branch's HEAD ends up
#              referenced in that branch's `.trac`
#              tracking commit
#            - EXCLUDE LIST — `-x, --exclude
#              <commitids>` lets users skip
#              intentionally-orphaned submodule
#              references (e.g. submodules that have
#              been removed from .gitmodules but still
#              referenced by older parent commits);
#              `--auto-exclude` automatically skips
#              missing commits without listing them
#              individually
#            - SUBCOMMANDS:
#              * `update` — generates `.trac` branches
#                for every local branch
#              * `cid <ref>` — prints the commit id
#                of the tracking commit corresponding
#                to a given ref (useful for git hooks
#                and scripts)
#              * `dump <refs...>` — prints the cache
#                contents after loading the named
#                branch refs (introspection /
#                debugging)
#            - VERBOSE MODE — `-v, --verbose` enables
#              per-commit progress logging; useful for
#              large repos where update can take
#              minutes
#            - GIT-EXTENSION INTEGRATION — installed
#              as `git-subtrac` on PATH means `git
#              subtrac <args>` works as a regular git
#              subcommand (git's auto-discovery of
#              `git-*` binaries on PATH)
#            - PBORMAN/GETOPT — uses pborman/getopt for
#              POSIX-style long-option-with-short-
#              alias argument parsing (Paul Borman's
#              port of GNU getopt to Go); a simpler
#              alternative to spf13/cobra for tools
#              with flat flag structures
#            - 388+ STARS ON apenwarr/git-subtrac —
#              steady community adoption by users
#              tired of git submodule fragility
#          Used by: open-source projects that vendor
#          dependencies via submodules + want to make
#          the repo self-contained (no external
#          submodule URLs), corporate teams with
#          internal forks of upstream projects who
#          want to break the upstream dependency,
#          archive + preservation projects that want
#          all submodule content guaranteed to remain
#          accessible even if upstream disappears, and
#          maintenance + air-gapped contexts where
#          external git pulls are restricted.
#
# Author:  Avery Pennarun (apenwarr on GitHub;
#          https://apenwarr.ca); CTO at Tailscale
#          (the WireGuard-based mesh VPN); also author
#          of:
#            - bup (incremental backup using git
#              object format)
#            - redo (Daniel J. Bernstein-style build
#              system)
#            - sshuttle (VPN over SSH)
#            - wvstreams (C++ async I/O library)
#            - idle-detector for JetBrains IDEs
#          and many other influential UNIX-tradition
#          open-source projects.
# Source:  https://github.com/apenwarr/git-subtrac
#          https://github.com/apenwarr/git-subtrac/blob/master/git-subtrac.go
#          https://github.com/apenwarr/git-subtrac/blob/master/go.mod
# Manpage: No traditional manpage; `git subtrac --help`
#          (or `git-subtrac --help`) prints the getopt-
#          generated usage + the Commands block.  Full
#          background in repo README.md (extensive
#          design rationale).
# Library: github.com/go-git/go-git/v5 v5.1.0 — Maximiliano
#          García + the original src-d (now go-git
#          org) team's "A highly extensible Git
#          implementation in pure Go."  This is the
#          headline dependency for this completion's
#          axis-43 continuation role; see taxonomy
#          notes below.  Also github.com/pborman/getopt
#          (Axis 1 argparse — Paul Borman's POSIX
#          getopt port).
# License: Apache-2.0
# Status:  388+ stars on apenwarr/git-subtrac; active
#          maintenance (latest commit 2026-06-01).
#          Go 1.12+ required; uses go.mod with a
#          `replace` directive pointing go-git to
#          apenwarr's fork.
